&nbsp;

Hello! I will be out of the country for the next week on a service trip to Guatemala. In the mean time, go outside!

&nbsp;

-S

There is no true replacement for enjoying time outdoors. Hiking in the mountains, climbing outside, or paddling in the waves are activities that can’t be replicated. Being outside is being outside.

However, if you need a little procrastination break in the library or are stranded in the urban jungle, here are some of my favorite websites, blogs, and podcasts to keep the adventurous spirit alive.

<em><a href="http://www.thecleanestline.com" target="_blank">The Cleanest Line:</a> </em>This is the company Patagonia’s blog. It includes stories and thoughts from Patagonia employees and ambassadors. While it seems like it would be a shameless plug for Patagonia gear, it really isn’t. Instead the blog documents the crazy travels of its ambassadors and cool environmental/sustainability initiatives. My favorite posts range from one about the logistics of van yoga to interviews with killer climbers.

Check is out at <a href="http://www.thecleanestline.com">www.thecleanestline.com</a>

[caption id="attachment_689" align="aligncenter" width="199" caption="Getting creative with van yoga"]<a href="http://www.collegeoutside.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/6a00d8341d07fd53ef0168e81fcf1f970c-800wi.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-689" src="http://www.collegeoutside.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/6a00d8341d07fd53ef0168e81fcf1f970c-800wi-199x300.jpg" alt="" width="199" height="300" /></a>[/caption]

&nbsp;

<em><a href="http://www.highinfatuation.com" target="_blank">High Infatuation: </a></em>This is a lifestyle/climbing/vegan living blog written by climber Stephanie Davis. Davis is a well-known climber and PrAna ambassador who is based out of Moab, Utah. High Infatuation offers great climbing advice (how to successfully tape blistered hands), yummy vegan recipes, and glimpses into her outdoor adventures. If you want to zone out and watch something beautiful, check out her collection of videos base-jumping and wingsuit flying. Absolutely incredible.

<a href="http://www.highinfatuation.com">www.highinfatuation.com</a>

&nbsp;

<em><a href="http://www.semi-rad.com" target="_blank">Semi-Rad</a>: </em>I was just introduced to this blog and I already love it. The posts are interesting and humorous ranging from “The Rules for Dating a Dirtbag” about the realities of dating fellow outdoors-ites to the issue of not sounding sophisticated in “Dude, is it OK if I call you Dude?” Funny and true, definitely check out <a href="http://www.semi-rad.com">www.semi-rad.com</a>

&nbsp;

<em><a href="http://www.prana.com/blog/" target="_blank">Prana Blog:</a> </em>This one is just fun. It definitely advertises Prana clothing more explicitly than Patagonia does on The Cleanest Line, but it still has some cool outdoors and environmental videos. If you make it to this blog, watch the “inside game” video series that features Chris Sharma, Dean Potter, and Steph Davis – they are all about how they control their thoughts and emotions to push the edge, free solo a route, or base jump.

<a href="http://www.prana.com/blog/">www.prana.com/blog/</a>

&nbsp;

<em><a href="http://enormocast.com/">The Enormocast</a>: </em>An entertaining podcast about climbing life. Hosted by climber and self-proclaimed dirtbag Chris Kalous, <em>The Enormocast</em> is a reinvention of the podcast <em>Off Belay.</em> Past episodes include an extended interview with Hayden Kennedy about the Cerro Torre controversy, Sam Lightner from the Access Fund, and Steph Davis about climbing and flying. While the podcast is still young, with only nine episodes, it is informative and amusing – give it a listen!

&nbsp;

<em><a href="http://www.dirtbagdiaries.com/"> The Dirtbag Diaries:</a> </em>This amazing podcast features stories and tales from adventurers in every walk of life. As a postcast, you can listen to these stories on the way to work or on your drive up to your favorite crag. Their blog also provides an awesome selection of music.

&nbsp;

<em><a href="http://www.assholeclimbers.com/" target="_blank">Asshole Climbers:</a> </em>Just read it. It's hilarious. Don't take them too seriously.

&nbsp;

Enjoy, but don’t spend too much time online. Get outside!
